 <!-- Write a program to read through the mbox-short.txt and figure out the 
 distribution by hour of the day for each of the messages. You can pull the hour 
 out from the 'From ' line by finding the time and then splitting the string a 
 second time using a colon. From stephen.marquard@uct.ac.za Sat Jan  5 09:14:16 2008
Once you have accumulated the counts for each hour, print out the counts, 
sorted by hour as shown below. -->

name = input("Enter file:")
if len(name) < 1:
    name = "mbox-short.txt"
handle = open(name)

hourtally = dict()

for line in handle: 
    newline = line.strip().split(" ") 
    <!-- # a list of strings containing the info -->
    timestamp = newline[4].split(":") 
    <!-- # access the 4th segment of the list for time -->
    hour = timestamp[0] 
    <!-- # access the first segment of the time to get hour -->
    hourtally[hour] = hourtally.get(hour,0) + 1 
<!-- toss the hour value into the hourtally histogram to get frequency -->

<!-- the hour is the key, so sort by key value and print in a list -->

for key,value in sorted(hourtally.items()):
    print(key,value)
        

